Stocks on the Sydney stock exchange lost more than five percent, but then decreased losses to 4.3 percent.
The stock market in Taiwan fell by 3.6 percent according to the local index.
“The timing of the rescue operation in the US is uncertain and will affect the financial markets worldwide,” said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority.
Hong Kong, although it belongs to China, determines its monetary policy itself, i.e. independent of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are moving at the same level as those in the United States.
U.S. lawmakers should return to the negotiating table as soon as possible, according to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, and pass the draft to support the financial system.
Otherwise, other countries would also be affected by the break-in.
A Bloodbath of American Stocks
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected the plan to support the financial system, for which up to 700 billion dollars (almost 12 trillion CZK) should be spent.
The lawmakers ignored President Bush’s call to support the plan.
In Bush’s view, the plan would regulate the underlying causes of the financial crisis and thus help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks experienced a bloodbath on Monday, and the main stock indices recorded the biggest break-in in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones Index fell by almost seven percent, with a similar break-in last recorded in 1987.
The index had already declined before the vote, but there was hardly any indication that the draft would not be passed in the House of Representatives, the index experienced a free case.
Congress agrees: U.S. government can pump $700 billion into banks
The top representatives of the American Congress and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of agreement on financial aid for the American financial system.
This is to be agreed at the beginning of next week.
U.S. lawmakers reached a breakthrough in talks over the adoption of a bailout plan in the form of a financial aid to the U.S. financial system in the amount of $700 billion (about 12 trillion crowns).
However, this does not mean victory yet.
Members of Congress must discuss some of the details of the agreement before they can publish the final version of the law and vote on it.
The plan to support the financial system will be negotiated at the U.S. Congress on Monday.
On Sunday, the chairman of the Banking and Financial Services Committee, Barney Frank, told Reuters.
According to various sources in the Senate, the plan could probably be voted on by Wednesday at the earliest.
According to economists, a message that the plan should be adopted should be the first significant psychological factor for a revival of the financial markets.
After that, however, there is a "renewal" due to the complicated mechanisms, how to help the markets also in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made significant progress.
We have clarified our different views on what a package should look like to stabilize the market,” Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to him, there could be a final vote on Sunday.
Representatives of the lawmakers met on the night of Sunday with the US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson to give the government fund its final form.
This provides for the purchase of unsold mortgage assets from financial companies, which plunge financial firms into serious losses and endanger the stability of the entire system.
“We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and that must also be effective on the market.
You still have to continue the health plan, but I think we’re on target,” Paulson said.
A signal for Asian businesses
The global financial crisis is also clearly falling in the stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to the Nevada Democratic Senator, Harry Reid, the lawmakers are trying to reach a final agreement before Sunday in Congress.
This is to reassure investors before trading on the Asian financial markets, which are in the first time zone, where a congressional decision could affect the trading on Monday.
So far, however, it is not entirely clear when both chambers of the American Congress will vote on the law, but there is also uncertainty as to whether the last minute negotiations could still fail on a problem.
The legislators hope that it will be passed in the next few days.
But the law will see some changes.
The total amount allocated to assist the system shall be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion is expected to be made available as soon as possible, as President George Bush demanded.
However, Congress can block the distribution of the remaining money if it has the impression that the program does not fulfill its function, namely at another $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush Appreciates Progress in Negotiations
While the President has a veto in this decision, Congress can vote against his veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program has remained, which was based on obtaining funds for the purchase of bad mortgage securities, the value of which has fallen, because hundreds of thousands of Americans are no longer able to repay their mortgages.
“We have worked out everything.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the law on Sunday, the Senate then on Monday,” Republican Senator Judd Gregg said.
With the progress, President Bush also showed himself satisfied with the progress.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said Bush was satisfied with the progress made on Saturday and “appreciates the bilateral effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy.”
Restriction of golden parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, the senior negotiator, said lawmakers had agreed on a responsibility for the money program, protecting taxpayers from losses, concluding concessions, and a timetable for funding the plan.
The new law is also intended to limit the so-called golden parachutes for directors of the companies involved in the program and sets up a committee to oversee the fund.
This is to be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We have worked very hard on this and made great progress towards an agreement that works and is important for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also expects help for homeowners who have problems with repaying their mortgage.
The government should negotiate new rates on mortgages it buys, with the goal of lowering the monthly costs for the debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
The proposed plan is a good idea, according to the chief economist of Patria Finance David Marek, but implementation will be very difficult.
“And that’s because you don’t know what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets are bought up.
This will be decisive for how the financial sector and the government share the losses among each other," Marek told the server iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan is approved now or early next week, Marek’s view is not decisive.
“It’s much more important that Congressmen agree to support the plan and that they say goodbye to it as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement that there is going to be an adoption is the most important thing at the moment,” Marek said.
