The first virtual provider is coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer practically all services, as they are also offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classics to lower prices.
Maybe he won’t be able to wait any longer.
The fact that the Czech mobile service providers work among the most expensive in Europe at all, we have often reported about this on Mobil.cz.
By the way, this was also confirmed by the telecommunications authority <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which pointed out that the price of an SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
According to the latest steps taken by the European Commission in regulating roaming charges, it is likely that there will be a paradoxical situation – for some customers of Czech mobile phone providers, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that really makes a campaign statement.
It may sound paradoxical, but in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
On the other hand, mobile providers like to argue that there is an extremely high level of competition in the Czech market.
Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), who had often stated in the past that there is no place for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It’s probably true that a classic provider with its own network doesn’t have a lot of chances anymore (by the way, he’d probably hardly even find frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual provider.
It was precisely the entry of virtual providers into the mobile phone market that brought with it a significant price reduction, which the classical mobile phone providers had to respond to.
Before companies such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market in the UK, there were similar voices as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can be really successful.
By the way, you don’t need to look for examples for long.
In February, we reported this about the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and thus become the country’s fifth largest provider.
Behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon, among others, in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need far fewer customers than a classic provider.
You do not need a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually come out as low-cost companies – they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which, however, is often accompanied by a less extensive service offering.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half as cheap as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to bet on a non-clickable target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
“Real guys choose Mobilking – the provider they like and can trust,” said David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could be used in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, he is relatively satisfied from the point of view of the service offer."
In the Czech Republic without chance, the mobile phone providers mean
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile service provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be mobileking.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look particularly hopeful.
There will be more of a market entry of Mobilking in other countries of our region," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, a spokeswoman for Penta Financial Group, told Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile service providers in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
For a long time now, your interest in starting a virtual mobile provider has been shown by the GTS Novara group, which wants to take another step towards becoming a real competitor of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed network, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the earlier, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this option with all Czech mobile phone providers.
With some of them, we have already been able to make progress in negotiations,” said Pavel Kaidl, a spokesman for the group.
Maybe there will be better times.
Unofficial information suggests that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
Until now, however, this is surrounded by an invincible wall of silence.
“At this point, we do not assume that there is room for a full-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has great specificity compared to other markets.
So far, we have not been approached by a subject with a complex and serious project in this area,” says Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> from the press department of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other providers also point out the specifics of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> adds in rare agreement with O2’s statement: “So far, we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project on which to build further.”
She added: “In T-Mobile’s network, there will hardly be a virtual provider until the end of the year.
At this moment, we should already have a concrete offer in order to be able to think like this in the short term."
Vodafone is more focused on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> says: "For negotiations with potential virtual providers, we are open, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
This is exactly what we consider from the customer’s point of view as the best.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to look for a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile internet.”
The responsible authorities - with the providers hand in hand
The move by mobile providers is easy to understand, another provider was called more competition, this would lead to falling prices and thus also to a decrease in profits.
So why should it be easier for such a competitor to enter the market?
The fact that the providers can pull on a string when it comes to something also proves the long back and forth about the emergence of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure towards <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> came at the time when U:fon came on the market, from the company T-Mobile.
This is also evidenced by the publicly available information from the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> websites.
But now U:fon is just a good argument as to why you shouldn’t allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile phone market has recently also been strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile phone provider.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and above all its services."
In view of this approach, however, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
This is not just about the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which unfortunately, unlike the United Kingdom and other highly developed countries, does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It is owned exclusively by the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
This, however, related to this whole problem to his very typical attitude.
"The market entry of a virtual mobile service provider would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile service provider and a virtual service provider over the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential interested parties was probably not interesting enough for the classical providers,” said Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa from the Department of Foreign Affairs of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS in his reply to our request.
Such a formulation would not come as a surprise from representatives of the providers.
This is more than a matter of concern from an authority that represents consumer interests and should, among other things, ensure that no one abuses its position on the market.
In particular, if Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: "In a foreign country where virtual providers work quite normally, it is to be observed that their entry into the market has contributed to a price reduction in mobile phone services."
But probably the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction are not in the interests of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
In this case, it is really shocking that almost all the three mobile phone providers are already in agreement with each other, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is at hand.
Just like the absolutely same gasoline price at the gas stations is certainly only chance and the result of a fierce competition.
"The Authority has not found any evidence in this matter that suggests action against the competition, and therefore has no reason to intervene in the matter in any way.
None of the providers has a dominant market position, so it does not have the corresponding increased responsibility for its actions on the market.
The necessary tools for opening up the mobile market for virtual providers are also likely to be missing from the regulatory authority for telecommunications,” Chalupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many contentious points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, drawn up by the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, after telecommunications from the perspective of economic competition is a single market.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile service providers has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different perspective - for the market entry of a virtual provider, the consent of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile provider has – logically – the monopoly for its network.
This means that it necessarily occupies a dominant position in a particular segment.
However, even if you do not agree with this argument, it should be at least a warning to the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile service providers are acting remarkably similar.
Complaints by a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novara) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all providers.
The discharge of responsibility to the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is then a fairly common trick in the telecommunications services, with which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, in the recently adopted novella of the Telecommunications Act, it has not succeeded in implementing the extension of the competences of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> to the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts have tried to improve the situation.
The representatives of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS only need to know all too well, but they probably have different interests.
It's all right when no one looks
First of all, the functioning of any pseudo-virtual provider, of which there are equal numbers in the Czech mobile networks remains unabated.
It is companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunication services, but only partially public.
Usually, these are companies that operate in the field of multi-level marketing.
Their own mobile phone services include Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only go to selected ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company acts towards the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile phone providers prohibit a similar resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it may be a violation of the contractual conditions that we will then deal with, which can lead to an end of the cooperation with the relevant society," Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> replied to our question about this problem.
However, it is quite improbable that such a thing does not occur among those responsible for the mobile phone providers.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, they can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such a procedure.
The activities of these companies do not result in negligible profits for them, but at the same time, unlike the actual virtual providers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> points out about possible problems: "The law allows for such types of speculation, despite everything, the services of these companies are used only by a very small percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone does not run on their name, so they cannot have it in full like the normal customers of mobile phone providers.”
But at least that would have been a strange thing to do.
There is also another question for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
Mobile providers close their eyes to such an approach, why do they block themselves against a virtual provider?
It is to be added that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has quite strong competences for the detection of such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to satisfy itself with the declaration of the providers, they do not know anything about it and their terms and conditions would prohibit this.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has already been stressed several times in the text, the entry into the market of virtual providers brought a significant price drop in the various services.
Virtually in all countries where virtual providers have been created, the classic providers have tried to prevent their creation practically more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - a market too small, or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, the regulatory bodies that tried to safeguard the interests of the mobile phone providers, but those of their customers, intervened precisely at these moments.
Whether it was through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they reached that the first virtual operator was created, followed by more.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing themselves all over the case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot escape the impression that uncertainty in the competences in these cases is more than favorable.
But let's not throw the flint into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider appears soon, the Czech mobile market may soon be in motion again.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile service provider, the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting other interested parties (to discriminate).
And the Czechs will finally not be calling more expensive than the rest of Europe.
