The Sudeten demanded a referendum from the United States
The Sudeten Germans had asked the United States to join the B<0xC3><0xB6>hmer Forest in 1945.
This emerges from a letter stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we can’t be part of Germany or Austria, at least we want to live under the umbrella of the United States of America.
With such a wish, some groups of Sudeten Germans were supposed to turn to the US president in 1945.
This is evidenced, among other things, by a letter that has been preserved in a private archive and which is now kept in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Germans of Krumau in the letter ask the American president not to allow the return of the "Sudetengau" - which was taken on the basis of the Munich agreement by Hitler - to Czechoslovakia.
“We have understood the situation correctly and really want to be sure of the words that the American units do not enter German territory as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators,” it said in a letter signed with the words “people whose fate lies at the heart of the Sudeten”.
Since the accession to Czechoslovakia leads the Sudeten Germans - in the knowledge of the Czech national character - to suspect that they would expect brutality, recklessness, misunderstanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American president to protect them from now and then.
“We can’t believe that you, regardless of the view of a quarter of a million people in this area, are appealing to a foreign state that is trying to suppress and eliminate minorities and has done nothing to help the Allies win,” the letter reads.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is allegedly the fear of reprisals by the "Czech oppressors".
If the U.S. President has doubts about the opinion of the Bohemian Forest Germans, it would be sufficient if he would initiate a referendum in the Bohemian Forest on whether the residents wanted to become part of the United States or live under the protection of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound somewhat na<0xC3><0xAF>ve in today’s knowledge of post-war history, it does, however, in the opinion of some contemporary witnesses, draw a good picture regarding the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at the time.
Even though the Bohemian Germans at least had to suspect that they would be negotiating their deportation from the Republic, only a few of them agreed on such a possibility at all.
Some waited for the United States and the United Kingdom to negotiate some sort of autonomy for the Sudeten.
Again, others believed that they could simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
It is also confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who comes from Budweis.
He was employed in the war as a Budweiser German at the Navy on the Baltic Sea.
When he came to British captivity at the end of the war and was taken to Holstein in a prisoner of war camp, dozens of other Bohemian Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
“They thought if they came home, they would be able to fit the Czech,” Chalupa said.
None of the German prisoners of war who had lived in Czechoslovakia before the war, in his opinion, expected him to be expelled from the Republic on the basis of the Bene<0xC5><0xA1> decrees.
