Debate on bilingual education: Education in an English-speaking environment
In this edition of the "Education Watch", Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the candidates' positions on bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, Senior Research Fellow in California Studies and Senior Director in Educational Sciences at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-author of the book "Not as Good as You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs a School Choice".
Addressing Hispanic voters is a complicated task.
Barrack Obama’s proposals on education are a typical example of this.
Obama’s election campaign mentions that “the probability of African-American and Hispanic students successfully completing school is lower than that of white students” – which is true.
To close this gap in performance, Obama’s education plan recommends, among other things, a bilingual transition phase in education for those who first learn English.
Yet the question to Obama is whether his use of bilingual education, which focuses on teaching in languages other than English, contradicts his interest in reducing the gap in school performance.
Let’s take for example “Sixth Street Prep,” a primary school in eastern Los Angeles.
The majority of the students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than a third of the students, many of whom have recently been in the country, are learning English.
Yet, in 2008, amazing 100 percent of fourth-grade students passed the state exam in math at a good level.
Also surprisingly, 93 percent of the children from the fourth year of school were rated as well in the English exam.
This amazing success was achieved with methods other than those preferred by Obama.
The Sixth Street School focuses on review and practice, on constant control of knowledge, and an attitude that tolerates no exceptions.
In addition, the school is practicing the approach by which the training takes place in an English-speaking environment, which is exactly the point that Obama should pay attention to, says Linda Mikels, the head of the school.
This approach places value on the almost exclusive use of the English language in professional training.
Mrs. Mikels, who rejects the idea of bilingual education, told me that the school had a remarkable success with a student who had just come from Mexico. 12 months later, you would enter the classroom and not be able to recognize him again.
“It works,” she remarked, “it works for us.”
Would Obama take a school like the "Sixth Street Prep" as a model for other schools with a large proportion of Latin American and other English-speaking students?
The school’s performance would make the answer to this question easy, but the educational policy positions within its own party (the national educational associations have long supported the idea of bilingual education) and its own consistent support for bilingual education make predictions about Obama’s answer uncertain.
While he agrees with the point that immigrants should learn English, he has recently trivialized the issue by noting that people should stop worrying about legislation aimed at "only English".
Instead, he said, "You should make sure your child can speak Spanish."
If Obama actually wants to close the power gap, he should carefully consider educational models that work rather than despise and trivialize them.
