The pride and the sufferings in the life of the black population, in a city of a very special kind
Hidden between the growths of the amusement parks around Orlando, a few miles away from the glittering, loud and gigantic drive, lies a quiet city in which the pride and complications of African American culture come to light.
Eatonville, the first completely black town in the country and the hometown of Zora Neale Hurstons, is no longer as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: "the city with 5 lakes, three croquettes, 300 brown hides, 300 good swimmers, more than enough guavas, 2 schools and no grass."
Today it is a pilgrimage site.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to commemorate the most famous author of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet, the city that describes it – and which made it a tourist destination – is, and remains, a place of a very special kind in many respects by taking it to the Florida travel guide produced by the Federal Writers’ Project at the time of the depression.
Eatonville is as independent, generous and private as in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man who “knows so little about us that he doesn’t know what’s going on with him.”
Even today, in a year when a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, is calling for an open conversation about race relations, many are still suffering from being watched by outsiders.
“We are very concerned about how our history is told,” said Hortense Jones, 59, from birth to a resident of the city and a member of the congregation of the city’s oldest church.
It must be true."
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is both a historical example of the black movement and a community of almost 2,400 inhabitants, in which the poverty rate is twice as high as the national average.
It is, on the one hand, a stronghold of literature and, on the other hand, an example of the sometimes condemned, sometimes praised, black culture of the rural south, which has its roots in American slavery.
It is not surprising that residents here are both proud and on the hat.
And so right, the concerns about Eatonville's image actually started with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world in books that came from the heart and were written in oral form, such as "Mules and Men" (1953) and "Their Eyes were watching God" (1973).
Five paragraphs in the Florida travel guide changed the city, located very close to Route 77, a road that leads through the often-forgotten center of Florida, to the shacks of black history and human drama.
Frech and Oskar both in real life and in literature, Hurston led readers to the store of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private affairs.
“Beyond the street to the left,” she wrote, “is the brown-whitely-striped modern school, with its well-maintained gardens and playgrounds that Howard Miller always cares about, even though he can barely read and write.”
She also mentioned the new man of Widow Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of any kind and what-and-always fits into classrooms."
In just a few hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with self-government, but also with illiteracy, second marriage, and sex.
This was certainly not a travel guide.
In fact, this was not a portrait that was appreciated by everyone.
“Zora described things as they were,” said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls who immortalized Hurston by citing the men who sang songs about her beauty that were full of sexual allusions.
She added: "Some people didn't like it."
One still remembers Hurtson here as a lively eccentric who returned regularly after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that when Hurston came to town in need, she usually did so without warning, in a noisy Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants, in a city that even today imagines something about her venerable style of clothing.
According to Mr. Franklin, most residents were fascinated, while many despised them.
“People were always happy to see Zora,” Mr Franklin said.
But "she never stayed too long," he added as he swinged in his chair, on a rear facing terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, in which Hurston was most likely baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were lost.
Together with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten them.
Although she was once a famous author, a contemporary Langstin Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was placed in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived, in an anonymous grave.
In Eatonville there were no great memorials, no public readings in great style.
“I don’t think they understood their contribution to the world or their heritage at all,” said Valerie Boyd, author of “Wrapped in Rainbows,” a biography of Hurston published in 2003.
The turn came in the 80s.
Orange County authorities wanted to put a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the slow two-lane main street of the community.
Orlando's suburbs had already pushed the highway 4 through the western edge of the city.
The proposal was submitted when Eatonville still recovered from a difficult phase in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the fight against racial mixing brought hatred into the community.
“At this time, a bunch of white boys often came and they threw oranges and stuff on the people sitting away,” Mr. Franklin said.
“There was even a woman who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car."
In 1955, in a letter to the Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court’s demand to force integration by calling its decision in Brown’s case against the school board “as insulting as respecting my race.”
Residents today say that although the abolition of racial segregation was positive in some ways, it weakened the group’s cohesion in Eatonville and the self-awareness of its youth.
"Black children were used to being embraced - I remember - one embraced his teacher in the morning and one embraced his teacher in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and managing director of the non-profit group for the protection of the Eatonville community.
This could be maintained for so long, she added, until teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
"You didn't hug his white teacher because he was a white teacher - I mean there's a cultural divide," Ms. Nathiri said.
However, civil rights have contributed to the creation of space for more Zora Neale Hurstons – black authors, actors, and artists who turned away from prejudices, as they did, with positive self-awareness and statements like: "How can anyone be free to guess?
I don't understand."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker set out on her way to Hurston's nameless grave and began to fight for the revival of her glory.
Five years later, a much-praised Hurston biography of Robert E. Hemenway was found in the bookshelves, and again made it part of the American literary canon.
The long-distance project came at a time when Eatonville’s most famous daughter was once again in the public light.
And this time Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a rescuer.
The community began planning a Hurston Festival in 1988 to show what the district could destroy with the construction of the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and every January many return for the celebration.
A few years later, the district turned away from its road construction plans.
"The plans of a five-lane highway revived the city, accelerated the whole thing at top speed, aroused real civic pride," Ms. Nathiri said.
Mrs. Boyd put it a little easier: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory against the long-distance project has contributed to a change in the city’s self-image.
There were more and more train trips, such as Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been going to church here since 1993, and locals began to re-evaluate the past.
Eatonville was included in the country-wide historical register in 1998.
A new one-storey library (of course named after Hurston) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville is still a special place in Florida: only 6 miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes feel like a backstreet in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded by only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(It is 90% black today.)
Outsiders looking for the history of Eatonville and its significance are often still treated with caution.
For most interviews, permission is required in advance and certain things - such as the mural of Eatonville's oldest church, painted by a white man and depicting black men in field work - must not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, such as Mrs. Jones, a courageous, self-confident teacher with a preference for dark red, still fear that her shielded community will be misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time as the Hurston Festival grew larger, an increased degree of home pride was also born.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw its entire race: beautiful, with all its problems, neither worse nor better and just as proud, creative and diligent, barking and mixing like any other race and people group in America.
It is the sincere love for this city that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return after college to Eatonville to work in the city administration or at the police station, which he says might need some help with.
And even the youngsters, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, eleven-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people who just walk through here will think, 'Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,'" Alondra Kenon said recently on a Sunday after the church.
“But if you actually stop and look at its history for a moment, it’s a very beautiful city.”
