Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its founding yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it has regained the public’s trust, which had been severely shaken by the blood-sucking scandal of the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Donor Service during the 1980s were contaminated with the HI virus and hepatitis C virus.
In the face of this drama and public dissatisfaction, in February 1994, the Government of Canada launched a public investigation led by Judge Horace Krever aimed at bringing light into the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy, and drafting guidelines to reverse this kind of catastrophism.
While Judge Krever still hesitated to submit his report, several provinces at the time set up a committee whose goal was to develop a new system for managing blood cans in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this task.
According to reports by Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood society to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
“In 1998, when Hema-Quebec took up its work, barely 38% of people had confidence in the blood conservation system in Quebec,” Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
By the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood cans and by working in this area over the following years, we have regained public confidence," she says, before proudly stressing that by the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of Quebec's population had confidence in Hema Quebec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that ‘trust is something extremely fragile’.
Since its inception on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has been acting on the principle of caution.
At that time, we experienced the occurrence of numerous cases of the human form of cattle madness in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jacob disease, tells this woman, who has been in charge since the foundation in 1998.
