So this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we applied makes sense.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NSTs) that allow it to prove directly in the blood of the donor the presence of the virus itself, and not that of the antibody against the virus, as was the case with the previously used tests.
The NST made it possible to shorten the incubation time that takes place between the time the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected by our techniques in the blood, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors could be infected without knowing it, and one could not recognize this, was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of getting HIV-infected blood.
In other words, it means that you have to distribute 12 million blood cans before someone gets infected with HIV.
