What Barrick Gold doesn’t understand – or doesn’t want to understand – is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada does this primarily because it rejects the brutal attitude of goldmines.
This public is willing to listen to and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilised exchange of arguments, and not in a framework that many perceive as a silly complaint (during the <0x60>public debate' Barrick Gold has just resorted to... using a demand to the authors of Noir Canada no longer address it to him.
Apart from Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, Barrick Gold’s lawsuit is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and truth-finding that are fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denies the right to cite credible sources and to discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to explore and discuss topics that the rich companies of this world do not like, who else can do that?
