The psychology of overspending – or why we’re willing to pay more
In the case of auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overestimate the wrong bidder.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the “Science” magazine, people in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, don’t want to give up and are therefore willing to pay even higher prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was supposed to play the lotto while the other participated in a playful action - in both cases, the active brain regions of the subjects were examined using functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to win money, however, increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the cerebral cortex, was measured in the losers of the auction, in which the opponent's overtaking plays an essential role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore considered that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
In order to support their thesis, the economists in the research group have also conducted research to track the money.
In this case, three groups should compete against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their bets.
Another group was also promised a $15 reward, in case they emerge as the winner of the game.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which was also lost in the event of a lost game.
So the difference between the two groups was simply that the emphasis was on one on winning while the other on losing.
As evidence of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, however, the members of the “against losing” group were willing to make higher stakes than those in the control or “win” group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
In fact, the behaviours observed at auctions so far have only been based on the joy of winning or risk avoidance.
The contradiction between these two theories was solved thanks to the imaging neurological procedures, so we now have a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When is the doctor to visit?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary, this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected is estimated to be one hundred thousand in this country, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - inflammation of the liver and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the pathogen, the hepatitis viruses are spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E by the digestive tract (for example by contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted by blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, secretion or saliva).
Travelers are advised to get vaccinated against viruses A and B at least, and there is no vaccine against virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A show up about two to three weeks after consuming the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and brittleness.
After that, the yellowing occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes light, the urine dark, and the recovery can last up to two to three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die each year from the more serious diseases caused by hepatitis B, such as liver cancer and hepatic cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that according to estimates, only one in ten people infected is in drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated it can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen mysteriously destroys the liver cells - in many cases, the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular control examinations, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable during a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the GP at the first signs of unknown origin.
Recognized in time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, thereby banishing the risk of infection and preventing the formation of cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, 2004 for the first time by patient representatives worldwide.
The aim of the action is to strengthen awareness of these chronic inflammation of the liver caused by viruses, their origin and the importance of early detection.
