What would be the best way to develop new accident prevention technologies if not to imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, the bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented in which the Nissan engineers were inspired by Hummeln in the creation of new accident avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C type autorobot-controlled biomimetic system, a mini car equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own, oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "shield", said Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, at the exhibition.
The compound eye of the bees, which can be seen in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role.
To mimic the function of the composite eye, the researchers came up with the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
This identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C in a 180-degree field of view within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision-preventing process.
The obstacle is recorded in fractions of seconds, and the autorobot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of the bees by turning the tires around the corresponding angle.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver takes place purely instinctively.
“If it wasn’t, the autorobot couldn’t react fast enough to avoid the obstacles,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the autorobot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer that is now considered inevitable within the accidents.
The whole process must reflect the behavior of the bees if they evade other bees.
And that has to happen in the fraction of a second.
However, the deviation, unlike the bees, can not take place up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, namely only in the direction of the reversibility of the tires.
While the bees here are endlessly open to avoid other bees, the researchers at the autorobot could only use rotational motion, or acceleration and braking.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient, and therefore have a longer service life than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process a few inputs per second and respond accordingly to them.
It doesn’t have to store it, or produce an intuitive, logical reaction using previous maneuvers, so it only uses a handful of KB memory on a regular basis.
It doesn’t require gigabyte and megabyte-heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of the immediate collision avoidance technology, which is expected to be in production as standard within the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by consciously steering the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to the destination.
