The super glue that lets you go up on walls
To defeat the forces of gravity thanks to an adhesive and be able to climb walls like Superman.
This is the subject of four American research centers, one of which has now seemingly almost reached its destination.
With an adhesive applied on an area of only 2.5 qcm, the researchers managed to fix a 100 kg body on a vertical wall.
The STUDIO – an American journal has published the results of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the research team is a further development of the adhesives already used, which use a particular carbon structure, called carbon nanotubes.
“The principle of adhesive can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged to a stack of spaghetti,” explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists have been inspired by the feet of the geckos, which are covered by microscopic claws that give the animal a perfect hold.
The tests carried out with various materials such as glass Teflon and sandpaper have shown that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than the holding capacity of the feet of the reptiles and at the same time "makes it easy to remove from the wall", says Liming Dai, a researcher at the Faculty of Engineering of the University of Dayton.
"This material could be used as a passable adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
Perhaps, but the researchers think of a less fascinating benefit, such as the connection of electrical devices, because the nanotubes are also conductors of heat and electricity.
Other areas of application could fall within the scope of space travel.
For the moment, the superheroes still have to wait.
