In an article by the American Chemical Society, California scientists present an adhesive made of microfibers that clean themselves from dust, like hair, by moving on a surface itself.
Medicines: never take with fruit juice
Be careful with grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed due to their refreshing quality and vitamin content, especially in the summer, can cause serious health damage when taken at the same time with certain vital medicines, as they can have an extreme effect on the absorption of these by the body.
David Bailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, repeatedly points to the risk of packaged as well as fresh fruit juices in conjunction with medication intake. As part of the 236th meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he again struck the alarm: Medicaid is sufficient to consume a glass of apple, orange or grapefruit
Grapefruit juice was already suspected to be responsible for increasing the effects of some drugs such as antibiotics, antiasthma, cardiovascular drugs, anxiolytic and neurological agents, to toxic levels.
PHARMACEUTICAL FORM – The same agency of the drug had warned doctors and patients about the dangers of this mixture in a report two years ago, and stressed to pay attention to what is drunk in conjunction with drugs such as diazepam or methadone.
ES IS NOT ONLY GRAPEFRUIT – According to the experts, orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that can inhibit the drugs.
The list of active substances inhibited by fruit juices is long.
Michele Carruba, Director of the Universit<0xC3><0xA0> Statale di Milano, said: “Such results are usually immediately communicated to the various international manufacturers, who are thus free to change consumer information.
