The Nobel Prize in Economics is awarded to American Paul Krugman for his analysis of trade patterns and the settlement of economic activities.
The 55-year-old Krugman is a Neo-Keynesian who teaches at Princeton University and is known for his regular articles for the New York Times.
Krugman is one of the biggest critics of the Bush administration’s economic and foreign policy.
A few months after the attacks of September 11, 2001, during the days of the Enron collapse, Krugman had claimed in a New York Times editorial that this second event was more crucial to U.S. history than the attacks.
A prediction that received not much controversy as an answer and was presented to the economist years later, but today proves to be completely correct.
“I’m surprised and shocked at how quickly the memory of the scandals as part of the collapses of Enron or Worldcom disappeared from the public eye,” Krugman said in a statement.
