Farewell to the old cinema Paradiso – the cities close their historic cinema halls
The historical cinemas close due to the favored multiplex cinemas.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes.”
This picture of the director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is currently happening in the large urban centers of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-seater complexes in the periphery, in the long run means death for the single-seater cinema in the center. A process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocably, but also carries the triggers of a cultural crime.
Mostly affected are historical places full of memories, "it's like losing a friend with whom you've laid down a piece of street full of emotions," says the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", who brought him the Oscar and the Grand Prix of Cannes 20 years ago.
The figures provided by the Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: in the last five years, the enormous amount of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; these tokens mostly paid for the cinemas in the big cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, and 6 in Naples, Naples, and Bologna.
The most affected regions include Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This shows that the main culprits are the multiplex cinemas, because it is precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy is leading the lists, 81 are in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
