When the energy comes out of the waves, suddenly the big ones run up.
It is a non-defeating source of money that covers more than 70% of the planet’s surface, and it is only now that the world’s major energy companies seem to understand this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that everyone is now looking at, and also looking to occupy, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and investigated for 70 years; these studies have not coincidentally intensified significantly since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil fell around 1980, the idea of marine energy was abandoned, but now environmental organizations and the rising price of oil are pushing for new impulses in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world’s energy needs could be covered by the energy generated by the ocean waves.
This is equivalent to doubling the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, the currents and tides were also added.
Giants in the attack.
The first company that now relies on marine energy is Enersis, who signed a contract to build a power plant in northern Portugal in 2005.
When this message was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy industry are investing in marine energy production.
“Chevron is investigating these technologies,” said a spokesman for a company known to the American giant in the Wall Street Journal, and is considering working with us.
This is about obtaining an approval from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to start a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign that is not to be underestimated, e.g. considering that oil is still being promoted by the United States in Alaska, and President Bush recently launched plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; the details are also unknown, as observers speak of an increasing interest.
Even better-informed technologies.
Experts are talking about a technology that is still in its infancy, not least because the last doubts on the part of environmentalists have not yet been clarified.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland are of a rather small size and do not seem to cause any serious environmental problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, it requires technologies with far greater impact on the environment.
There are several options: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the swimmer via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The current is then sent to the coast via underwater lines.
Up to now, there are four planned facilities of this type, which are only waiting for state approval, and some of the energy gained could also be used for military installations.
However, Verdant Power already produces energy for a department store and parking lot using underwater turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feed the generator through the resulting rotational motion.
According to Verdant, a long queue of potential customers is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Acquisition Research, a particular interest immediately deserves the potential that is in the tides.
Although this is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are still better predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and also the waves, and therefore a more reliable source of electricity.
It is tidal energy that has led states such as New York, Maine and Alaska and other coastal states to invest $7.5 million already in 2008 – up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
